sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE THE LEAD AFTER WINNING THE INNINGS.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons scored four points for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by 39 points in two days to take the lead in the county championship.

Their stay at the top may be short-lived, however, as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in a rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.

After bowling Somerset out for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before being bowled out for 296 with England discard Andy Caddick taking three for 83.
Somerset, trailing by 213, started solidly in their second inning before Simmons stepped in and struck out them for 174.
Essex, however, seem confident of regaining their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a firm grip in their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, who is considered a surplus player for England's one-day matches, played 158 strokes, his first championship century this season, and Essex reached 372 and led by 82 in the first innings.
In the end Yorkshire turned that advantage into 37 points but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on at 119 for five and praying for rain.

At The Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man sacked by England, continued to silence his critics as he followed his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hope Mark Butcher, who scored 70 points and Surrey closed on 429 for seven, a lead of 234 points.
Derbyshire continued his chase for his first championship title since 1936 when he reduced Worcestershire's score to 133 in the second round to five, still 100 shots short of avoiding defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody scored six for 82, but Chris Adams (123) and Tim O'Gorman (109) led Derbyshire to 471 points and a first lead of 233.
After the frustration of having their opening day's play badly affected by the weather, Kent upped the tempo and dismissed Nottinghamshire for 214.
Paul Johnson flashed 84 points but former England fast bowler Martin McCague scored four for 55.
On the stumps, Kent achieved a score of 108-3.

The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for 15 million pounds ($23.4 million), replaces Tony Adams, who led the team during June's European Championships, and former captain David Platt.
Both Adams and Platt are injured and will miss Sunday's opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova.
Shearer has taken up the captaincy on trial, but new coach Glenn Hoddle has said he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not become captain.
"I'm sure it won't be a problem, I'm sure Alan is the man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could do it, but when I spoke to Alan he was all for it and really wanted to do it.
"It's very hard to come to a 100% conclusion about something like this in four days...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the situation in the team, even when he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 teammate Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the team on Friday due to injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS BANNED AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

Rotor Volgograd must play another home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 0-1 home defeat that ended Rotor's brief period at the top of the league.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on Sept. 3.
The club, which knocked out Manchester United in last year's UEFA Cup, was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position with 11 games left to play in the championship.
Volgograd are three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, but have a game in hand over the leaders and two ahead of the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMANIAN ROBERT DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran will step into the ring on Saturday to try to keep his long career alive.
Duran, 45, will face little-known 30-year-old Mexican Ariel Cruz in Panama City in a non-title super middleweight bout.
The fight, which is Duran's first on home soil in a decade, is being billed here as "the return of a legend" and Duran is still talking like he's in his prime.
This fight is to prepare me.
I'm not going to retire," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"With every game, he's on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's best boxers," said Panama Boxing Association president Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will secure him a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho won a controversial points decision over Panama in June in Atlantic City in a title fight.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN HAVE TWICE ASSERTED THEMSELVES UNDER LIGHTS IN THE SPRING.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of twists and turns at the US Open.
Eleventh-seeded Washington was unable to repeat his miraculous Wimbledon comeback, losing to a rampant Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 on the Stadium Court after two hours and 51 minutes of battle.
Next to the grandstand, the tenth-seeded Rios lost to another player who has something in common with Wimbledon - the tough guy Jeff Tarang.
The temperamental left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although sixth-seeded former champion Agassi had to wriggle out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 loss. He won 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who came from 1-5 down in the Wimbledon semifinals against Todd Martin to drop two sets in the third set, looked poised for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title two weeks ago in New Haven, served for the win at 5-4 in the third set before Washington came back to take the match.
"I kept telling myself, 'Give yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept calm and was proud of myself - normally I would have folded the tent and gone home."
The hard-serving O'Brien, a former U.S. college champion, hit 17 aces and finally overpowered the indomitable Washington.
The fifth set stayed on serve until the sixth game when Washington, after saving one break point with a forehand winner down the line, played a backhand into the net to put O'Brien up 4:2.
The Texan held serve for 5:2 with two aces and then converted his eighth match point when Washington found the net with another backhand from 40:0.
"You're just fighting and trying to get him to play a little bit.
I think he pulled back a little bit in a few moments," Washington said."
But I think he served pretty well when he had to. "

Tarango, who earned a $28,000 fine and a ban from this year's All-England Club tournament for his Wimbledon tantrum two years ago, argued and taunted fans during a two-hour, 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
A thunderous cheer supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American, who drew all the attention to himself.
"I'm an emotional player," said the 104th-ranked Tarango. "
I think I played very well and focused today. "
The match was decided by a tiebreak of the third set, which the American won 7:5 to the dismay of the spectators.
"I love the audience, even though they boo me every day.
That will get me pumped up and make me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"The best tennis I played in college was when fraternities threw beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
"He's still complaining too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think it is.
I think I played really badly.
It was hard to play at night.
The balls were flying really fast.
I lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see it during the day.
I'm playing an American, that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the court. "
At the end of the match, Tarango kissed the crowd sarcastically before wobbling into Rios' cheering section in a joking salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, he's unabashedly rooting against me.
When I won, I thought I could dazzle them a bit. "
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's best quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to play the center position, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham, who was selected to the Pro Bowl three times, racked up 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organization and the great Philadelphia fans for their support throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"While I am sad to leave, I look forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11-year tenure in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
Cunningham, who was selected in the second round of the 1985 draft, completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed on as a broadcaster.
